[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] In Itô calculus, the **Euler–Maruyama method** (also simply called the **Euler method**) is a method for the approximate numerical solution of a stochastic differential equation (SDE).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] It is an extension of the Euler method for ordinary differential equations to stochastic differential equations named after Leonhard Euler and Gisiro Maruyama.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] The same generalization cannot be done for any arbitrary deterministic method.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] with initial condition *X*0 = *x*0, where *W**t* denotes the Wiener process, and suppose that we wish to solve this SDE on some interval of time [0, *T*].
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] The random variables Δ*W**n* are independent and identically distributed normal random variables with expected value zero and variance Δ*t*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] Like other approximation methods, the accuracy of the Euler–Maruyama scheme is analyzed through comparison to an underlying continuous solution.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] at time $t\in [0,T]$ , where $\mu$ and $\sigma$ denote deterministic "drift" and "diffusion" functions, respectively, and $W_{t}$ is the Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] Here, ${\hat {X}}_{N}$ corresponds to the final state of the discrete process ${\hat {X}}$ , which approximates $X_{T}$ by taking N steps of length $\Delta t=T/N$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] for any bounded and continuous function g .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] for any $\delta \in (0,\delta _{0})$ , the approximation converges strongly with order $\gamma _{s}$ to the continuous process X ; likewise, ${\hat {X}}$ converges weakly to X with order $\gamma _{w}$ if the same inequality holds for the expectation of $g({\hat {X}}_{N})-g(X_{T})$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] By using a Taylor series expansion of the exponential function in the analytic solution, we can get a formula for the exact update in a time-step.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] confirming strong order $1/2$ convergence.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] Another numerical aspect to consider is stability.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] The path's second moment is $\mathbb {E} |X_{t}|^{2}\propto \exp \left((2\lambda +\sigma ^{2})t\right)$ , so long-time decay of the solution occurs only when $2\lambda +\sigma ^{2}<0$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] The Euler–Maruyama scheme preserves variance decay in this case provided that $\Delta t\leq {\frac {-1}{\lambda ^{2}}}\left(2\lambda +\sigma ^{2}\right)$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] An area that has benefited significantly from SDEs is mathematical biology.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/euler-maruyama-method] As many biological processes are both stochastic and continuous in nature, numerical methods of solving SDEs are highly valuable in the field.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/kolmogorov-backward-equations-diffusion] The **Kolmogorov backward equation (KBE)** and its adjoint, the Kolmogorov forward equation, are partial differential equations (PDE) that arise in the theory of continuous-time continuous-state Markov processes.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/kolmogorov-backward-equations-diffusion] Both were published by Andrey Kolmogorov in 1931.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/kolmogorov-backward-equations-diffusion] Later it was realized that the forward equation was already known to physicists under the name Fokker–Planck equation; the KBE on the other hand was new.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/kolmogorov-backward-equations-diffusion] The Kolmogorov forward equation is used to evolve the state of a system forward in time.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/kolmogorov-backward-equations-diffusion] A common boundary condition is to ask that the future state is contained in some subset of states $B,$ the **target set**.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/kolmogorov-backward-equations-diffusion] The backward Kolmogorov equation can be used to derive the Feynman–Kac formula.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/kolmogorov-backward-equations-diffusion] Because F solves the PDE, the first integral is zero.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/kolmogorov-backward-equations-diffusion] The Feynman–Kac representation can be used to find the PDE solved by the transition densities of solutions to SDEs.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/kolmogorov-backward-equations-diffusion] Assuming Lebesgue measure as the reference, write $|B|$ for its measure.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] In physics, a **Langevin equation** (named after Paul Langevin) is a stochastic differential equation describing how a system evolves when subjected to a combination of deterministic and fluctuating ("random") forces.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The dependent variables in a Langevin equation typically are collective (macroscopic) variables changing only slowly in comparison to the other (microscopic) variables of the system.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The fast (microscopic) variables are responsible for the stochastic nature of the Langevin equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] One application is to Brownian motion, which models the fluctuating motion of a small particle in a fluid.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The force acting on the particle is written as a sum of a viscous force proportional to the particle's velocity (Stokes' law), and a *noise term* ${\boldsymbol {\eta }}(t)$ representing the effect of the collisions with the molecules of the fluid.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The $\delta$ -function form of the time correlation means that the force at a time t is uncorrelated with the force at any other time.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This is an approximation: the actual random force has a nonzero correlation time corresponding to the collision time of the molecules.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] However, the Langevin equation is used to describe the motion of a "macroscopic" particle at a much longer time scale, and in this limit the $\delta$ -correlation and the Langevin equation becomes virtually exact.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This approximation of $\delta$ -correlated (white) noise breaks down under certain conditions, especially in the presence of external driving forces that bring the system out of equilibrium, such as shear flow or for dense charged systems under AC external drive.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This is also the case of the Langevin equation for relativistic systems, where the $\delta$ -correlated noise assumption is in tension with the principle of locality.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Another common feature of the Langevin equation is the occurrence of the damping coefficient $\lambda$ in the correlation function of the random force, which in an equilibrium system is an expression of the Einstein relation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] A strictly $\delta$ -correlated fluctuating force ${\boldsymbol {\eta }}(t)$ is not a function in the usual mathematical sense, and even the derivative $\mathrm {d} \mathbf {v} /\mathrm {d} t$ is not defined in this limit.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This problem disappears when the Langevin equation is written in integral form $m\mathbf {v} =m\mathbf {v} _{0}+\int _{t_{0}}^{t}{\big (}{-\lambda }\mathbf {v} +{\boldsymbol {\eta }}(t){\big )}\,\mathrm {d} t.$ Therefore, the differential form is only an abbreviation for its time integral.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The general mathematical term for equations of this type is "stochastic differential equation".
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Another mathematical ambiguity occurs for Langevin equations with multiplicative noise, which refers to noise terms that are multiplied by a non-constant function of the dependent variables, e.g., $|{\boldsymbol {v}}(t)|\,{\boldsymbol {\eta }}(t)$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] If a multiplicative noise is intrinsic to the system, its definition is ambiguous, as it is equally valid to interpret it according to Stratonovich or Itô scheme (see Itô calculus).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Nevertheless, physical observables are independent of the interpretation, provided the latter is applied consistently when manipulating the equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This is necessary because the symbolic rules of calculus differ depending on the interpretation scheme.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] If the noise is external to the system, the appropriate interpretation is the Stratonovich one.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] There is a formal derivation of a generic Langevin equation from classical mechanics.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This generic equation plays a central role in the theory of critical dynamics, and other areas of nonequilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The equation for Brownian motion above is a special case.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] An essential step in the derivation is the division of the degrees of freedom into the categories *slow* and *fast*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] For example, local thermodynamic equilibrium in a liquid is reached within a few collision times, but it takes much longer for densities of conserved quantities like mass and energy to relax to equilibrium.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Thus, densities of conserved quantities, and in particular their long-wavelength components, are slow-variable candidates.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This division can be expressed formally with the Zwanzig projection operator.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Nevertheless, the derivation is not completely rigorous from a mathematical physics perspective because it relies on assumptions that lack rigorous proof, and instead are justified only as plausible approximations of physical systems.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Let $A=\{A_{i}\}$ denote the slow variables.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The dependence $\mathrm {d} \lambda _{i,j}/\mathrm {d} A_{j}$ of $\lambda$ on A is negligible in most cases.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The symbol ${\mathcal {H}}=-\ln(p_{0})$ denotes the Hamiltonian of the system, where $p_{0}(A)$ is the equilibrium probability distribution of the variables A .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Finally, $[A_{i},A_{j}]$ is the projection of the Poisson bracket of the slow variables $A_{i}$ and $A_{j}$ onto the space of slow variables.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The equation of motion $\mathrm {d} \mathbf {x} /\mathrm {d} t=\mathbf {p} /m$ for $\mathbf {x}$ is exact: there is no fluctuating force $\eta _{x}$ and no damping coefficient $\lambda _{x,p}$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] There is a close analogy between the paradigmatic Brownian particle discussed above and Johnson noise, the electric voltage generated by thermal fluctuations in a resistor.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The diagram shows an electric circuit consisting of a resistance *R* and a capacitance *C*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The slow variable is the voltage *U* between the ends of the resistor.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This equation may be used to determine the correlation function $\langle U(t)\,U(t')\rangle ={\frac {k_{\text{B}}T}{C}}\exp \left(-{\frac {|t-t'|}{RC}}\right)\approx 2Rk_{\text{B}}T\delta (t-t'),$ which becomes white noise (Johnson noise) when the capacitance C becomes negligibly small.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The dynamics of the order parameter $\varphi$ of a second-order phase transition slows down near the critical point and can be described with a Langevin equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Other universality classes (the nomenclature is "model A", ..., "model J") contain a diffusing order parameter, order parameters with several components, other critical variables and/or contributions from Poisson brackets.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] A particle in a fluid is described by a Langevin equation with a potential energy function, a damping force, and thermal fluctuations given by the fluctuation dissipation theorem.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] If the potential is quadratic, then the constant energy curves are ellipses, as shown in the first figure.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] If there is dissipation but no thermal noise, a particle continually loses energy to the environment, and its time-dependent phase portrait (velocity vs position) corresponds to an inward spiral toward 0 velocity.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] By contrast, thermal fluctuations continually add energy to the particle and prevent it from reaching exactly 0 velocity.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Rather, the initial ensemble of stochastic oscillators approaches a steady state in which the velocity and position are distributed according to the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] In the second plot, the long-time velocity distribution (blue) and position distributions (orange) in a harmonic potential ( $U={\tfrac {1}{2}}kx^{2}$ ) is plotted with the Boltzmann probabilities for velocity (green) and position (red).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] In particular, the late time behavior depicts thermal equilibrium.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The following plot corresponds to solutions of the complete Langevin equation for a lightly damped harmonic oscillator, obtained using the Euler–Maruyama method.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The left panel shows the time evolution of the phase portrait at different temperatures.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The right panel captures the corresponding equilibrium probability distributions.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] At zero temperature, the velocity slowly decays from its initial value (the red dot) to zero, over the course of a handful of oscillations, due to damping.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] For nonzero temperatures, the velocity can be kicked to values higher than the initial value due to thermal fluctuations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] At long times, the velocity remains nonzero, and the position and velocity distributions correspond to that of thermal equilibrium.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The general solution to the equation of motion is $\mathbf {v} (t)=\mathbf {v} (0)e^{-t/\tau }+\int _{0}^{t}\mathbf {a} (t')e^{-(t-t')/\tau }\,dt',$ where $\tau =m\mu$ is the correlation time of the noise term.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] Besides, the value of $\lim _{t\to \infty }\langle v^{2}(t)\rangle =\lim _{t\to \infty }R_{vv}(t,t)$ is set to be equal to $3k_{\text{B}}T/m$ , such that it obeys the equipartition theorem.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] If the system is initially at thermal equilibrium already with $v^{2}(0)=3k_{\text{B}}T/m$ , then $\langle v^{2}(t)\rangle =3k_{\text{B}}T/m$ for all t , meaning that the system remains at equilibrium at all times.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The velocity $\mathbf {v} (t)$ of the Brownian particle can be integrated to yield its trajectory $\mathbf {r} (t)$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] On the other hand, $\langle r^{2}(t\gg \tau )\rangle \simeq 6k_{\text{B}}T\tau t/m=6\mu k_{\text{B}}Tt=6Dt$ , which indicates an irreversible, dissipative process.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] If the external potential is conservative and the noise term derives from a reservoir in thermal equilibrium, then the long-time solution to the Langevin equation must reduce to the Boltzmann distribution, which is the probability distribution function for particles in thermal equilibrium.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The term $\eta (t)$ is white noise, characterized by $\langle \eta (t)\,\eta (t')\rangle =2k_{\text{B}}T\lambda \delta (t-t')$ (formally, the Wiener process).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] One way to solve this equation is to introduce a test function f and calculate its average.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] In some situations, one is primarily interested in the noise-averaged behavior of the Langevin equation, as opposed to the solution for particular realizations of the noise.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This section describes techniques for obtaining this averaged behavior that are distinct from—but also equivalent to—the stochastic calculus inherent in the Langevin equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] A Fokker–Planck equation is a deterministic equation for the time-dependent probability density $P(A,t)$ of stochastic variables A .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The Fokker–Planck equation for an underdamped Brownian particle is called the Klein–Kramers equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] In d -dimensional free space, corresponding to $V(\mathbf {r} )={\text{const}}$ on $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , this equation can be solved using Fourier transforms.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The functional determinant and associated mathematical subtleties drop out if the Langevin equation is discretized in the natural (causal) way, where $A(t+\Delta t)-A(t)$ depends on $A(t)$ but not on $A(t+\Delta t)$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] It turns out to be convenient to introduce auxiliary *response variables* ${\tilde {A}}$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] This formulation is typically referred to as either the Martin–Siggia–Rose formalism or the Janssen-De Dominicis formalism after its developers.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/langevin-equation] The mathematical formalism for this representation can be developed on abstract Wiener space.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/milstein-method] In mathematics, the **Milstein method** is a technique for the approximate numerical solution of a stochastic differential equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/milstein-method] It is named after Grigori Milstein who first published it in 1974.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/milstein-method] Consider the autonomous Itō stochastic differential equation: $\mathrm {d} X_{t}=a(X_{t})\,\mathrm {d} t+b(X_{t})\,\mathrm {d} W_{t}$ with initial condition $X_{0}=x_{0}$ , where $W_{t}$ denotes the Wiener process, and suppose that we wish to solve this SDE on some interval of time $[0,T]$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/milstein-method] Note that when $b'(Y_{n})=0$ (i.e. the diffusion term does not depend on $X_{t}$ ) this method is equivalent to the Euler–Maruyama method.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/milstein-method] The Milstein scheme has both weak and strong order of convergence $\Delta t$ which is superior to the Euler–Maruyama method, which in turn has the same weak order of convergence $\Delta t$ but inferior strong order of convergence ${\sqrt {\Delta t}}$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/milstein-method] For this derivation, we will only look at geometric Brownian motion (GBM), the stochastic differential equation of which is given by: $\mathrm {d} X_{t}=\mu X\mathrm {d} t+\sigma XdW_{t}$ with real constants $\mu$ and $\sigma$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/milstein-method] The numerical solution is presented in the graphic for three different trajectories.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Many differential equations cannot be solved exactly.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] For practical purposes, however – such as in engineering – a numeric approximation to the solution is often sufficient.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The algorithms studied here can be used to compute such an approximation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] An alternative method is to use techniques from calculus to obtain a series expansion of the solution.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Ordinary differential equations occur in many scientific disciplines, including physics, chemistry, biology, and economics.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] In addition, some methods in numerical partial differential equations convert the partial differential equation into an ordinary differential equation, which must then be solved.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] where f is a function $f:[t_{0},\infty )\times \mathbb {R} ^{d}\to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , and the initial condition $y_{0}\in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ is a given vector.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] *First-order* means that only the first derivative of *y* appears in the equation, and higher derivatives are absent.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Without loss of generality to higher-order systems, we restrict ourselves to *first-order* differential equations, because a higher-order ODE can be converted into a larger system of first-order equations by introducing extra variables.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] For example, the second-order equation *y*′′ = −*y* can be rewritten as two first-order equations: *y*′ = *z* and *z*′ = −*y*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] In this section, we describe numerical methods for IVPs, and remark that *boundary value problems* (BVPs) require a different set of tools.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] In a BVP, one defines values, or components of the solution *y* at more than one point.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Because of this, different methods need to be used to solve BVPs.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] For example, the shooting method (and its variants) or global methods like finite differences, Galerkin methods, or collocation methods are appropriate for that class of problems.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The Picard–Lindelöf theorem states that there is a unique solution, provided *f* is Lipschitz-continuous.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Numerical methods for solving first-order IVPs often fall into one of two large categories: linear multistep methods, or Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] A further division can be realized by dividing methods into those that are explicit and those that are implicit.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Explicit examples from the linear multistep family include the Adams–Bashforth methods, and any Runge–Kutta method with a lower diagonal Butcher tableau is explicit.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] A loose rule of thumb dictates that stiff differential equations require the use of implicit schemes, whereas non-stiff problems can be solved more efficiently with explicit schemes.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The so-called general linear methods (GLMs) are a generalization of the above two large classes of methods.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] From any point on a curve, you can find an approximation of a nearby point on the curve by moving a short distance along a line tangent to the curve.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This formula is usually applied in the following way.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] We choose a step size *h*, and we construct the sequence $t_{0},t_{1}=t_{0}+h,t_{2}=t_{0}+2h,\dots$ We denote by $y_{n}$ a numerical estimate of the exact solution $y(t_{n})$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This is the *Euler method* (or *forward Euler method*, in contrast with the *backward Euler method*, to be described below).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The method is named after Leonhard Euler who described it in 1768.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The Euler method is an example of an *explicit* method.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This means that the new value *y**n*+1 is defined in terms of things that are already known, like *y**n*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The backward Euler method is an *implicit* method, meaning that we have to solve an equation to find *y**n*+1.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] One often uses fixed-point iteration or (some modification of) the Newton–Raphson method to achieve this.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] It costs more time to solve this equation than explicit methods; this cost must be taken into consideration when one selects the method to use.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The advantage of implicit methods such as (**6**) is that they are usually more stable for solving a stiff equation, meaning that a larger step size *h* can be used.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Exponential integrators describe a large class of integrators that have recently seen a lot of development.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] or it has been locally linearized about a background state to produce a linear term $-Ay$ and a nonlinear term ${\mathcal {N}}(y)$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The Euler method is often not accurate enough.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] In more precise terms, it only has order one (the concept of *order* is explained below).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This caused mathematicians to look for higher-order methods.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] One possibility is to use not only the previously computed value *y**n* to determine *y**n*+1, but to make the solution depend on more past values.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This yields a so-called *multistep method*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Perhaps the simplest is the leapfrog method which is second order and (roughly speaking) relies on two time values.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Another possibility is to use more points in the interval $[t_{n},t_{n+1}]$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This leads to the family of Runge–Kutta methods, named after Carl Runge and Martin Kutta.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] One of their fourth-order methods is especially popular.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] A good implementation of one of these methods for solving an ODE entails more than the time-stepping formula.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] It is often inefficient to use the same step size all the time, so *variable step-size methods* have been developed.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Usually, the step size is chosen such that the (local) error per step is below some tolerance level.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This means that the methods must also compute an *error indicator*, an estimate of the local error.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] An extension of this idea is to choose dynamically between different methods of different orders (this is called a *variable order method*).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Methods based on Richardson extrapolation, such as the Bulirsch–Stoer algorithm, are often used to construct various methods of different orders.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Many methods do not fall within the framework discussed here.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Some IVPs require integration at such high temporal resolution and/or over such long time intervals that classical serial time-stepping methods become computationally infeasible to run in real-time (e.g.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] IVPs in numerical weather prediction, plasma modelling, and molecular dynamics).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Parallel-in-time (PinT) methods have been developed in response to these issues in order to reduce simulation runtimes through the use of parallel computing.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Early PinT methods (the earliest being proposed in the 1960s) were initially overlooked by researchers due to the fact that the parallel computing architectures that they required were not yet widely available.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] With more computing power available, interest was renewed in the early 2000s with the development of Parareal, a flexible, easy-to-use PinT algorithm that is suitable for solving a wide variety of IVPs.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The advent of exascale computing has meant that PinT algorithms are attracting increasing research attention and are being developed in such a way that they can harness the world's most powerful supercomputers.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The most popular methods as of 2023 include Parareal, PFASST, ParaDiag, and MGRIT.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Numerical analysis is not only the design of numerical methods, but also their analysis.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] A numerical method is said to be *convergent* if the numerical solution approaches the exact solution as the step size *h* goes to 0.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] All the methods mentioned above are convergent.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The *local (truncation) error* of the method is the error committed by one step of the method.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The method is said to be *consistent* if $\lim _{h\to 0}{\frac {\delta _{n+k}^{h}}{h}}=0.$ The method has *order* p if $\delta _{n+k}^{h}=O(h^{p+1})\quad {\text{as }}h\to 0.$ Hence a method is consistent if it has an order greater than 0.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The (forward) Euler method (4) and the backward Euler method (6) introduced above both have order 1, so they are consistent.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Most methods being used in practice attain higher order.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Consistency is a necessary condition for convergence, but not sufficient; for a method to be convergent, it must be both consistent and zero-stable.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] A related concept is the *global (truncation) error*, the error sustained in all the steps one needs to reach a fixed time t .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Explicitly, the global error at time t is $y_{N}-y(t)$ where $N=(t-t_{0})/h$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The global error of a p -th order one-step method is $O(h^{p})$ ; in particular, such a method is convergent.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This statement is not necessarily true for multi-step methods.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] For some differential equations, application of standard methods—such as the Euler method, explicit Runge–Kutta methods, or multistep methods (for example, Adams–Bashforth methods)—exhibit instability in the solutions, though other methods may produce stable solutions.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This "difficult behaviour" in the equation (which may not necessarily be complex itself) is described as *stiffness*, and is often caused by the presence of different time scales in the underlying problem.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] For example, a collision in a mechanical system like in an impact oscillator typically occurs at much smaller time scale than the time for the motion of objects; this discrepancy makes for very "sharp turns" in the curves of the state parameters.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Stiff problems are ubiquitous in chemical kinetics, control theory, solid mechanics, weather forecasting, biology, plasma physics, and electronics.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] One way to overcome stiffness is to extend the notion of differential equation to that of differential inclusion, which allows for and models non-smoothness.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Below is a timeline of some important developments in this field.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] Boundary value problems (BVPs) are usually solved numerically by solving an approximately equivalent matrix problem obtained by discretizing the original BVP.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] The most commonly used method for numerically solving BVPs in one dimension is called the Finite Difference Method.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] This method takes advantage of linear combinations of point values to construct finite difference coefficients that describe derivatives of the function.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] In both of these formulae, $h=x_{i}-x_{i-1}$ is the distance between neighbouring *x* values on the discretized domain.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] One then constructs a linear system that can then be solved by standard matrix methods.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] and solve the resulting system of linear equations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] On first viewing, this system of equations appears to have difficulty associated with the fact that the equation involves no terms that are not multiplied by variables, but in fact this is false.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/numerical-methods-for-ordinary-differential-equations] At *i* = 1 and *n* − 1 there is a term involving the boundary values $u(0)=u_{0}$ and $u(1)=u_{n}$ and since these two values are known, one can simply substitute them into this equation and as a result have a non-homogeneous system of linear equations that has non-trivial solutions.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] In mathematics of stochastic systems, the **Runge–Kutta method** is a technique for the approximate numerical solution of a stochastic differential equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] It is a generalisation of the Runge–Kutta method for ordinary differential equations to stochastic differential equations (SDEs).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] Importantly, the method does not involve knowing derivatives of the coefficient functions in the SDEs.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] Consider the Itō diffusion X satisfying the following Itō stochastic differential equation $dX_{t}=a(X_{t})\,dt+b(X_{t})\,dW_{t},$ with initial condition $X_{0}=x_{0}$ , where $W_{t}$ stands for the Wiener process, and suppose that we wish to solve this SDE on some interval of time $[0,T]$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] The random variables $\Delta W_{n}$ are independent and identically distributed normal random variables with expected value zero and variance $\delta$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] This scheme has strong order 1, meaning that the approximation error of the actual solution at a fixed time scales with the time step $\delta$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] It has also weak order 1, meaning that the error on the statistics of the solution scales with the time step $\delta$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] See the references for complete and exact statements.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] The functions a and b can be time-varying without any complication.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] The method can be generalized to the case of several coupled equations; the principle is the same but the equations become longer.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] A newer Runge—Kutta scheme also of strong order 1 straightforwardly reduces to the improved Euler scheme for deterministic ODEs.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] Consider the vector stochastic process ${\vec {X}}(t)\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ that satisfies the general Ito SDE $d{\vec {X}}={\vec {a}}(t,{\vec {X}})\,dt+{\vec {b}}(t,{\vec {X}})\,dW,$ where drift ${\vec {a}}$ and volatility ${\vec {b}}$ are sufficiently smooth functions of their arguments.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] Repeat this time step $(t_{m}-t_{0})/h$ times in order to integrate the SDE from time $t=t_{0}$ to $t=t_{m}$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] The scheme integrates Stratonovich SDEs to $O(h)$ provided one sets $S_{k}=0$ throughout (instead of choosing $\pm 1$ ).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] Higher-order schemes also exist, but become increasingly complex.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] Rößler developed many schemes for Ito SDEs, whereas Komori developed schemes for Stratonovich SDEs.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/runge-kutta-method-sde] Rackauckas extended these schemes to allow for adaptive-time stepping via Rejection Sampling with Memory (RSwM), resulting in orders of magnitude efficiency increases in practical biological models, along with coefficient optimization for improved stability.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] A **stochastic differential equation** (**SDE**) is a differential equation in which one or more of the terms is a stochastic process, resulting in a solution which is also a stochastic process.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] SDEs have many applications throughout pure mathematics and are used to model various behaviours of stochastic models such as prices of listed company shares, random growth models or physical systems that are subjected to thermal fluctuations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] SDEs have a random differential that is in the most basic case random white noise calculated as the distributional derivative of a Brownian motion or more generally a semimartingale.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] However, other types of random behaviour are possible, such as jump processes like Lévy processes or semimartingales with jumps.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Stochastic differential equations are in general neither differential equations nor random differential equations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Random differential equations are conjugate to stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Stochastic differential equations can also be extended to differential manifolds.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Some of these early examples were linear stochastic differential equations, also called Langevin equations after French physicist Langevin, describing the motion of a harmonic oscillator subject to a random force.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The mathematical theory of stochastic differential equations was developed in the 1940s through the groundbreaking work of Japanese mathematician Kiyosi Itô, who introduced the concept of stochastic integral and initiated the study of nonlinear stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Another approach was later proposed by Russian physicist Stratonovich, leading to a calculus similar to ordinary calculus.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The most common form of SDEs in the literature is an ordinary differential equation with the right hand side perturbed by a term dependent on a white noise variable.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In most cases, SDEs are understood as continuous time limit of the corresponding stochastic difference equations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This understanding of SDEs is ambiguous and must be complemented by a proper mathematical definition of the corresponding integral.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Such a mathematical definition was first proposed by Kiyosi Itô in the 1940s, leading to what is known today as the Itô calculus.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Another construction was later proposed by Russian physicist Stratonovich, leading to what is known as the Stratonovich integral.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The Itô integral and Stratonovich integral are related, but different, objects and the choice between them depends on the application considered.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The Itô calculus is based on the concept of non-anticipativeness or causality, which is natural in applications where the variable is time.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] An alternative view on SDEs is the stochastic flow of diffeomorphisms.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This understanding is unambiguous and corresponds to the Stratonovich version of the continuous time limit of stochastic difference equations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Associated with SDEs is the Smoluchowski equation or the Fokker–Planck equation, an equation describing the time evolution of probability distribution functions.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The generalization of the Fokker–Planck evolution to temporal evolution of differential forms is provided by the concept of stochastic evolution operator.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In physical science, there is an ambiguity in the usage of the term "Langevin SDEs".
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] While Langevin SDEs can be of a more general form, this term typically refers to a narrow class of SDEs with gradient flow vector fields.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This class of SDEs is particularly popular because it is a starting point of the Parisi–Sourlas stochastic quantization procedure, leading to a N=2 supersymmetric model closely related to supersymmetric quantum mechanics.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] From the physical point of view, however, this class of SDEs is not very interesting because it never exhibits spontaneous breakdown of topological supersymmetry, i.e., (overdamped) Langevin SDEs are never chaotic.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Brownian motion or the Wiener process was discovered to be exceptionally complex mathematically.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The Wiener process is almost surely nowhere differentiable; thus, it requires its own rules of calculus.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] There are two dominating versions of stochastic calculus, the Itô stochastic calculus and the Stratonovich stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Each of the two has advantages and disadvantages, and newcomers are often confused whether the one is more appropriate than the other in a given situation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Guidelines exist (e.g. Øksendal, 2003) and conveniently, one can readily convert an Itô SDE to an equivalent Stratonovich SDE and back again.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Still, one must be careful which calculus to use when the SDE is initially written down.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Numerical methods for solving stochastic differential equations include the Euler–Maruyama method, Milstein method, Runge–Kutta method (SDE), Rosenbrock method, and methods based on different representations of iterated stochastic integrals.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In physics, SDEs have wide applicability ranging from molecular dynamics to neurodynamics and to the dynamics of astrophysical objects.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] More specifically, SDEs describe all dynamical systems, in which quantum effects are either unimportant or can be taken into account as perturbations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] SDEs can be viewed as a generalization of the dynamical systems theory to models with noise.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This is an important generalization because real systems cannot be completely isolated from their environments and for this reason always experience external stochastic influence.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] There are standard techniques for transforming higher-order equations into several coupled first-order equations by introducing new unknowns.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] If X is a linear space and g are constants, the system is said to be subject to additive noise, otherwise it is said to be subject to multiplicative noise.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] For additive noise, the Itô and Stratonovich forms of the SDE generate the same solution, and it is not important which definition is used to solve the SDE.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] For multiplicative noise SDEs the Itô and Stratonovich forms of the SDE are different, and care should be used in mapping between them.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] For a fixed configuration of noise, SDE has a unique solution differentiable with respect to the initial condition.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Nontriviality of stochastic case shows up when one tries to average various objects of interest over noise configurations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In this sense, an SDE is not a uniquely defined entity when noise is multiplicative and when the SDE is understood as a continuous time limit of a stochastic difference equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In this case, SDE must be complemented by what is known as "interpretations of SDE" such as Itô or a Stratonovich interpretations of SDEs.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Nevertheless, when SDE is viewed as a continuous-time stochastic flow of diffeomorphisms, it is a uniquely defined mathematical object that corresponds to Stratonovich approach to a continuous time limit of a stochastic difference equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In physics, the main method of solution is to find the probability distribution function as a function of time using the equivalent Fokker–Planck equation (FPE).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The Fokker–Planck equation is a deterministic partial differential equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] It tells how the probability distribution function evolves in time similarly to how the Schrödinger equation gives the time evolution of the quantum wave function or the diffusion equation gives the time evolution of chemical concentration.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Alternatively, numerical solutions can be obtained by Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The notation used in probability theory (and in many applications of probability theory, for instance in signal processing with the filtering problem and in mathematical finance) is slightly different.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] It is also the notation used in publications on numerical methods for solving stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This notation makes the exotic nature of the random function of time $\xi ^{\alpha }$ in the physics formulation more explicit.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In strict mathematical terms, $\xi ^{\alpha }$ cannot be chosen as an ordinary function, but only as a generalized function.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The mathematical formulation treats this complication with less ambiguity than the physics formulation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] where B denotes a Wiener process (standard Brownian motion).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The equation above characterizes the behavior of the continuous time stochastic process *X**t* as the sum of an ordinary Lebesgue integral and an Itô integral.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This is so because the increments of a Wiener process are independent and normally distributed.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The function *μ* is referred to as the drift coefficient, while *σ* is called the diffusion coefficient.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The stochastic process *X**t* is called a diffusion process, and satisfies the Markov property.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The formal interpretation of an SDE is given in terms of what constitutes a solution to the SDE.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] There are two main definitions of a solution to an SDE, a strong solution and a weak solution Both require the existence of a process *X**t* that solves the integral equation version of the SDE.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The difference between the two lies in the underlying probability space ( $\Omega ,\,{\mathcal {F}},\,P$ ).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] A weak solution consists of a probability space and a process that satisfies the integral equation, while a strong solution is a process that satisfies the equation and is defined on a given probability space.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The Yamada–Watanabe theorem makes a connection between the two.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] which is the equation for the dynamics of the price of a listed company share in the Black–Scholes options pricing model of financial mathematics.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This leads to models that can deal with the volatility smile in financial mathematics.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] was used by Louis Bachelier as the first model for stock prices in 1900, known today as Bachelier model.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] There are also more general stochastic differential equations where the coefficients *μ* and *σ* depend not only on the present value of the process *X**t*, but also on previous values of the process and possibly on present or previous values of other processes too.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In that case the solution process, *X*, is not a Markov process, and it is called an Itô process and not a diffusion process.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] When the coefficients depends only on present and past values of *X*, the defining equation is called a stochastic delay differential equation.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] A generalization of stochastic differential equations with the Fisk-Stratonovich integral to semimartingales with jumps are the SDEs of *Marcus type*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The Marcus integral is an extension of McShane's stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] which is the equation for the dynamics of the return of the price of a listed company share under the hypothesis that returns display a Log-normal distribution.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Under this hypothesis, the methodologies developed by Marcello Minenna determines prediction interval able to identify abnormal return that could hide market abuse phenomena.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] More generally one can extend the theory of stochastic calculus onto differential manifolds and for this purpose one uses the Fisk-Stratonovich integral.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] For each $x\in M$ the map $A(x):E\to T_{x}M$ is linear and $A(\cdot )e\in \Gamma (TM)$ for each $e\in E$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] holds P -almost surely, where $(df)_{X}:T_{x}M\to T_{f(x)}M$ is the differential at X .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] It follows from the fact that $f(X)$ for each test function $f\in C_{c}^{\infty }(M)$ is a semimartingale, that X is a *semimartingale on M*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Although Stratonovich SDEs are the natural choice for SDEs on manifolds, given that they satisfy the chain rule and that their drift and diffusion coefficients behave as vector fields under changes of coordinates, there are cases where Ito calculus on manifolds is preferable.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] A theory of Ito calculus on manifolds was first developed by Laurent Schwartz through the concept of Schwartz morphism, see also the related 2-jet interpretation of Ito SDEs on manifolds based on the jet-bundle.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This interpretation is helpful when trying to optimally approximate the solution of an SDE given on a large space with the solutions of an SDE given on a submanifold of that space, in that a Stratonovich based projection does not result to be optimal.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This has been applied to the filtering problem, leading to optimal projection filters.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Usually the solution of an SDE requires a probabilistic setting, as the integral implicit in the solution is a stochastic integral.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] If it were possible to deal with the differential equation path by path, one would not need to define a stochastic integral and one could develop a theory independently of probability theory.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] as a single deterministic differential equation for every $\omega \in \Omega$ , where $\Omega$ is the sample space in the given probability space ( $\Omega ,\,{\mathcal {F}},\,P$ ).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Other definitions of the iterated integral lead to deterministic pathwise equivalents of different stochastic integrals, like the Stratonovich integral.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This has been used for example in financial mathematics to price options without probability.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] As with deterministic ordinary and partial differential equations, it is important to know whether a given SDE has a solution, and whether or not it is unique.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The following is a typical existence and uniqueness theorem for Itô SDEs taking values in *n*-dimensional Euclidean space **R***n* and driven by an *m*-dimensional Brownian motion *B*; the proof may be found in Øksendal (2003, §5.2).
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] More generally one can also look at stochastic differential equations on manifolds.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Whether the solution of this equation explodes depends on the choice of $\alpha$ .
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] This condition guarantees the existence and uniqueness of a so-called *maximal solution*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Suppose $\alpha$ is continuous and satisfies the above local Lipschitz condition and let $F:\Omega \to U$ be some initial condition, meaning it is a measurable function with respect to the initial σ-algebra.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] Let $\zeta :\Omega \to {\overline {\mathbb {R} }}_{+}$ be a predictable stopping time with $\zeta >0$ almost surely.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] $\zeta$ is also a so-called *explosion time*.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] where $Y_{t}=h(X_{t})$ where h is defined as before.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In supersymmetric theory of SDEs, stochastic dynamics is defined via stochastic evolution operator acting on the differential forms on the phase/state space of the model.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] In this formulation of stochastic dynamics, all SDEs possess topological supersymmetry which represents the preservation of the continuity of the phase space by continuous time flow.
[src:stochastic-differential-equations/stochastic-differential-equation] The spontaneous breakdown of this supersymmetry is the mathematical essence of the ubiquitous dynamical phenomenon known across disciplines as chaos.
